What to Do First?

Notes: When performing EDA on a single variable, you want to investigate and visualize how the data looks from various angles. The first thing you should be looking at is which variables seem to be the most important in your dataset and important to your analysis. You want think back about what is important to questions that you are trying to answer. ***

Perceived Audience Size

Notes: Based on Moiras Investigation, people underestimate their audience by about 3/4th. This means that their guessed audience size is only about a fourth of the actual audience size. When investigating this problem, Moira plotted a bunch of histograms.

Faceting

Notes: Faceting is the idea of splitting up graphs into multiple graphs based on a particular variable. facet_wrap is best used when generating plots for one variable. facet_grid is best used when you have two or more variables. A link about Faceting is provided here

qplot(x=dob_day,data = pf) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks= 1:31) +
  facet_wrap(~dob_month,ncol=3)

Lets take another look at our plot. What stands out to you here?

Response: That the abnormal spike seems to be on New Years Day ***

Be Skeptical - Outliers and Anomalies

Notes: Outliers can have many causes. They could be an extreme case or could represent bad data, or the limitations of your data. For example, and extreme value could be replaced by a more normal value or vice versa. ***

Moiras Outlier

Notes: In Moiras case, there was one outlier that was in the extreme case, causing the plot to be a single bar. After removing the outlier and change the scale to zoom in further, she was able to get a better picture of the data. Sometimes outliers may need to be removed. #### Which case do you think applies to Moiras outlier? Response: bad data about an extreme case ***

Limiting the Axes

Notes: To avoid looking at long-tailed data, the axes needs to be adjusted. This can be done using the xlim option as part of qplot, or entering an additional layer using scale_x_continuous layer.

qplot(x=friend_count,data=pf) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,1000))
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Exploring with Bin Width

Notes: In Moiras investigation, by adjusting the binwidth, she was able to see that most people guessed their perceived audience as numbers that mulitples of ten. Very few people guessed numbers in between. ***

Adjusting the Bin Width

Notes:Here we adjust the binwidth to get rid of the warning message in the console. This is done by setting the binwidth parameter in the qplot function. You can also adjust the breakpoints in the graph by using the breaks parameter in the scale_x_continuous function. More information about scales function can be found here

qplot(x=friend_count,data = pf,binwidth = 25) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0,1000), breaks = seq(0,1000,50))

Omitting NA Values

Notes: To omit the NA values in our gender column, we modify the data to take in the subset of data that does not have a NA value for gender. You can also perform this using the na.omit() function, but this may be too aggressive (It may omit genuine NA values).

qplot(x = friend_count, data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), binwidth = 10) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000),breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) + 
  facet_wrap(~gender)

Statistics by Gender

Notes: To get the number of females and males can given using the table function. To get the average number of friends by gender, you can use the by function. The by functions takes a parameter, how you want to split(a categorical variable or a list of indices), and a function to run on the first two parameters. We will use the summary function in this example

table(pf$gender)

Labeling Plots

Notes: Plots are labeled by using the xlab and ylab parameters in qplot. When performing EDA, it is not important for the graphs to be perfect, but good enough to perform the necessary analysis and gain insights.

qplot(x=tenure/365,data=pf, binwidth = 0.25,
      xlab = 'Number of years using Facebook',
      ylab = 'Numbers of users in sample',
      color = I('black'), fill = I('#099DD9')) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0,7), breaks = seq(1,7,1 ))

Add a Scaling Layer

Notes: When changing the data to a log10 scale, it changes the scale of the x-axis, whereas using the scale_x_log10 layer maintains the actual count axis.

p1 <- qplot(x=friend_count, data = pf,
            color = I('black'), fill = I('#099DD9'))
p2 <- p1 + scale_x_log10()

p3 <- p1 + scale_x_sqrt()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol=1)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Box Plots

Notes: Boxplots generates the Inter-quartile range for a distribution. the difference in boxplots than histograms is that the y-axis is going to be our friend count and the x-axis is going to be our categorical variable(gender)

It is best use the coord_cartesian layer as it will not remove any values and will match up nicely with the summary function output.

qplot(x = gender, y=friend_count,
      data = subset(pf,!is.na(gender)), geom = 'boxplot') +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,250))

by(pf$friend_count,pf$gender,summary)
## pf$gender: female
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

## -------------------------------------------------------- 
## pf$gender: male

Getting Logical

Notes: You may want to convert distributions that have a lot of zeros into logical data (true, or false). Below we use the ifelse function. This function takes the condition as the first parameter, the value of the if condition, followed by the value of the else condition.

summary(pf$mobile_likes)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0     0.0     4.0   106.1    46.0 25110.0
summary(pf$mobile_likes > 0)
##    Mode   FALSE    TRUE    NA's 
## logical   35056   63947       0
pf$mobile_check_in <- NA
pf$mobile_check_in <- ifelse(pf$mobile_likes > 0,1,0)
pf$mobile_check_in <- factor(pf$mobile_check_in)
summary(pf$mobile_check_in)
##     0     1 
## 35056 63947
pf$mobile_check_in <- NA
pf$mobile_check_in <- ifelse(pf$mobile_likes > 0,TRUE,FALSE)
sum(pf$mobile_check_in > 0)/length(pf$mobile_check_in)
## [1] 0.6459097

Response: The percent of checkins using mobile is 65% ***
